#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "The boot loader &grub;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:11
#, no-c-format
msgid "This chapter describes how to configure &grub;, the boot loader used in &productnamereg;. <phrase os=\"sled;sles\">It is the successor to the traditional GRUB boot loader&mdash;now called <quote>GRUB Legacy</quote>. &grub; has been the default boot loader in &productnamereg; since version 12.</phrase> A &yast; module is available for configuring the most important settings. The boot procedure as a whole is outlined in <xref linkend=\"cha-boot\"/> . For details on Secure Boot support for UEFI machines, see <xref linkend=\"cha-uefi\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:30
#, no-c-format
msgid "Main differences between GRUB legacy and &grub;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:34
#, no-c-format
msgid "The configuration is stored in different files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:39
#, no-c-format
msgid "More file systems are supported (for example, Btrfs)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:44
#, no-c-format
msgid "Can directly read files stored on LVM or RAID devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:49
#, no-c-format
msgid "The user interface can be translated and altered with themes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:54
#, no-c-format
msgid "Includes a mechanism for loading modules to support additional features, such as file systems, etc."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:60
#, no-c-format
msgid "Automatically searches for and generates boot entries for other kernels and operating systems, such as Windows."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "Includes a minimal Bash-like console."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:73
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuration file structure"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:75
#, no-c-format
msgid "The configuration of &grub; is based on the following files:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:81
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:83
#, no-c-format
msgid "This file contains the configuration of the &grub; menu items. It replaces <filename>menu.lst</filename> used in GRUB Legacy. <filename>grub.cfg</filename> should not be edited&mdash;it is automatically generated by the command <command>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:95
#, no-c-format
msgid "This optional file is directly sourced by <filename>grub.cfg</filename> at boot time and can be used to add custom items to the boot menu. Starting with &productname; <phrase os=\"sles;sled\">12 SP2</phrase> <phrase os=\"osuse\">Leap 42.2</phrase> these entries are also parsed when using <command>grub-once</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:107
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/default/grub</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:109
#, no-c-format
msgid "This file controls the user settings of &grub; and normally includes additional environmental settings such as backgrounds and themes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:117
#, no-c-format
msgid "Scripts under <filename>/etc/grub.d/</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:119
#, no-c-format
msgid "The scripts in this directory are read during execution of the command <command>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> . Their instructions are integrated into the main configuration file <filename>/boot/grub/grub.cfg</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:128
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/sysconfig/bootloader</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid "This configuration file holds certain basic settings like the boot loader type and whether to enable UEFI Secure Boot support."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:137
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename arch=\"x86_64\">/boot/grub2/x86_64-efi</filename> , <filename arch=\"power\">/boot/grub2/power-ieee1275</filename> <phrase os=\"sles\">, <filename arch=\"zseries\">/boot/grub2/s390x</filename></phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:139
#, no-c-format
msgid "These configuration files contain architecture-specific options."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:146
#, no-c-format
msgid "&grub; can be controlled in multiple ways. Boot entries from an existing configuration can be selected from the graphical menu (splash screen). The configuration is loaded from the file <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> which is compiled from other configuration files (see below). All &grub; configuration files are considered system files, and you need &rootuser; privileges to edit them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:156
#, no-c-format
msgid "Activating configuration changes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:157
#, no-c-format
msgid "After having manually edited &grub; configuration files, you need to run <command>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> to activate the changes. However, this is not necessary when changing the configuration with &yast;, because &yast; automatically runs this command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:167
#, no-c-format
msgid "The file <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:168
#, no-c-format
msgid "The graphical splash screen with the boot menu is based on the &grub; configuration file <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> , which contains information about all partitions or operating systems that can be booted by the menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:174
#, no-c-format
msgid "Every time the system is booted, &grub; loads the menu file directly from the file system. For this reason, &grub; does not need to be re-installed after changes to the configuration file. <filename>grub.cfg</filename> is automatically rebuilt with kernel installations or removals."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>grub.cfg</filename> is compiled from the file <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename> and scripts found in the <filename>/etc/grub.d/</filename> directory when running the command <command>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> . Therefore you should never edit the file manually. Instead, edit the related source files or use the &yast; <guimenu>Boot Loader</guimenu> module to modify the configuration as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-grub2-yast2-config\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:194
#, no-c-format
msgid "The file <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:195
#, no-c-format
msgid "More general options of &grub; belong here, such as the time the menu is displayed, or the default OS to boot. To list all available options, see the output of the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: grub2.xml:200
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;grep \"export GRUB_DEFAULT\" -A50 /usr/sbin/grub2-mkconfig | grep GRUB_"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:201
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can introduce custom variables and use them later in the scripts found in the <filename>/etc/grub.d</filename> directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:206
#, no-c-format
msgid "After having edited <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename> , update the main configuration file with <command>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:212
#, no-c-format
msgid "Scope"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:216
#, no-c-format
msgid "All options set in this file are general options that affect all boot entries. Specific options for &xen; kernels or the &xen; hypervisor can be set via the GRUB_*_XEN_* configuration options. See below for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:225
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:227
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sets the boot menu entry that is booted by default. Its value can be a numeric value, the complete name of a menu entry, or <quote>saved</quote> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:232
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=2</literal> boots the third (counted from zero) boot menu entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:236
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=\"2&gt;0\"</literal> boots the first submenu entry of the third top-level menu entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=\"Example boot menu entry\"</literal> boots the menu entry with the title <quote>Example boot menu entry</quote> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:245
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=saved</literal> boots the entry specified by the <command>grub2-once</command> or <command>grub2-set-default</command> commands. While <command>grub2-reboot</command> sets the default boot entry for the next reboot only, <command>grub2-set-default</command> sets the default boot entry until changed. <command>grub2-editenv list</command> lists the next boot entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:257
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:259
#, no-c-format
msgid "Waits the specified number of seconds for the user to press a key. During the period no menu is shown unless the user presses a key. If no key is pressed during the time specified, the control is passed to <literal>GRUB_TIMEOUT</literal> . <literal>GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT=0</literal> first checks whether <keycap function=\"shift\"/> is pressed and shows the boot menu if yes, otherwise immediately boots the default menu entry. This is the default when only one bootable OS is identified by &grub;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:272
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT_QUIET</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:274
#, no-c-format
msgid "If <literal>false</literal> is specified, a countdown timer is displayed on a blank screen when the <literal>GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT</literal> feature is active."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:282
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_TIMEOUT</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:284
#, no-c-format
msgid "Time period in seconds the boot menu is displayed before automatically booting the default boot entry. If you press a key, the timeout is cancelled and &grub; waits for you to make the selection manually. <literal>GRUB_TIMEOUT=-1</literal> causes the menu to be displayed until you select the boot entry manually."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:295
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:297
#, no-c-format
msgid "Entries on this line are added at the end of the boot entries for normal and recovery mode. Use it to add kernel parameters to the boot entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:305
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:307
#, no-c-format
msgid "Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> but the entries are appended in the normal mode only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:314
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_RECOVERY</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:316
#, no-c-format
msgid "Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> but the entries are appended in the recovery mode only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:323
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_XEN_REPLACE</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:325
#, no-c-format
msgid "This entry replaces the <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> parameters for all &xen; boot entries."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:332
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_XEN_REPLACE_DEFAULT</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:334
#, no-c-format
msgid "Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_XEN_REPLACE</literal> but it only replaces parameters of <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:342
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_XEN</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:344
#, no-c-format
msgid "This entry specifies the kernel parameters for the &xen; guest kernel only&mdash;the operation principle is the same as for <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:352
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_XEN_DEFAULT</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:354
#, no-c-format
msgid "Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_XEN</literal> &mdash;the operation principle is the same as for <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:362
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_TERMINAL</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enables and specifies an input/output terminal device. Can be <literal>console</literal> (PC BIOS and EFI consoles), <literal>serial</literal> (serial terminal), <literal>ofconsole</literal> (Open Firmware console), or the default <literal>gfxterm</literal> (graphics-mode output). It is also possible to enable more than one device by quoting the required options, for example, <literal>GRUB_TERMINAL=\"console serial\"</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:377
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_GFXMODE</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:379
#, no-c-format
msgid "The resolution used for the <literal>gfxterm</literal> graphical terminal. You can only use modes supported by your graphics card (VBE). The default is ‘auto’, which tries to select a preferred resolution. You can display the screen resolutions available to &grub; by typing <command>videoinfo</command> in the &grub; command line. The command line is accessed by typing <keycap>C</keycap> when the &grub; boot menu screen is displayed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:388
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can also specify a color depth by appending it to the resolution setting, for example, <literal>GRUB_GFXMODE=1280x1024x24</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:396
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_BACKGROUND</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:398
#, no-c-format
msgid "Set a background image for the <literal>gfxterm</literal> graphical terminal. The image must be a file readable by &grub; at boot time, and it must end with the <literal>.png</literal> , <literal>.tga</literal> , <literal>.jpg</literal> , or <literal>.jpeg</literal> suffix. If necessary, the image is scaled to fit the screen."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:409
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>GRUB_DISABLE_OS_PROBER</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:411
#, no-c-format
msgid "If this option is set to <literal>true</literal> , automatic searching for other operating systems is disabled. Only the kernel images in <filename>/boot/</filename> and the options from your own scripts in <filename>/etc/grub.d/</filename> are detected."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:421
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>SUSE_BTRFS_SNAPSHOT_BOOTING</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:423
#, no-c-format
msgid "If this option is set to <literal>true</literal> , &grub; can boot directly into Snapper snapshots. For more information, see <xref linkend=\"sec-snapper-snapshot-boot\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:431
#, no-c-format
msgid "For a complete list of options, see the <link xlink:href=\"http://www.gnu.org/software/grub/manual/grub.html#Simple-configuration\"> GNU GRUB manual</link> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:439
#, no-c-format
msgid "Scripts in <filename>/etc/grub.d</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid "The scripts in this directory are read during execution of the command <command>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> . Their instructions are incorporated into <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> . The order of menu items in <filename>grub.cfg</filename> is determined by the order in which the files in this directory are run. Files with a leading numeral are executed first, beginning with the lowest number. <filename>00_header</filename> is run before <filename>10_linux</filename> , which would run before <filename>40_custom</filename> . If files with alphabetic names are present, they are executed after the numerically named files. Only executable files generate output to <filename>grub.cfg</filename> during execution of <command>grub2-mkconfig</command> . By default all files in the <filename>/etc/grub.d</filename> directory are executable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:457
#, no-c-format
msgid "Persistent custom content in <filename>grub.cfg</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:458
#, no-c-format
msgid "Because <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> is recompiled each time <command>grub2-mkconfig</command> is run, any custom content is lost. To insert your lines directly into <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> without losing them after <command>grub2-mkconfig</command> is run, insert them between"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: grub2.xml:465
#, no-c-format
msgid "### BEGIN /etc/grub.d/90_persistent ###"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:466
#, no-c-format
msgid "and"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: grub2.xml:469
#, no-c-format
msgid "### END /etc/grub.d/90_persistent ###"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:470
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <filename>90_persistent</filename> script ensures that such content is preserved."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:474
#, no-c-format
msgid "A list of the most important scripts follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:480
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>00_header</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:482
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sets environmental variables such as system file locations, display settings, themes and previously saved entries. It also imports preferences stored in the <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename> . Normally you do not need to make changes to this file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:492
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>10_linux</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:494
#, no-c-format
msgid "Identifies Linux kernels on the root device and creates relevant menu entries. This includes the associated recovery mode option if enabled. Only the latest kernel is displayed on the main menu page, with additional kernels included in a submenu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:503
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>30_os-prober</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:505
#, no-c-format
msgid "This script uses <command>os-prober</command> to search for Linux and other operating systems and places the results in the &grub; menu. There are sections to identify specific other operating systems, such as Windows or macOS."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:514
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>40_custom</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:516
#, no-c-format
msgid "This file provides a simple way to include custom boot entries into <filename>grub.cfg</filename> . Make sure that you do not change the <literal>exec tail -n +3 $0</literal> part at the beginning."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:525
#, no-c-format
msgid "The processing sequence is set by the preceding numbers with the lowest number being executed first. If scripts are preceded by the same number the alphabetical order of the complete name decides the order."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:531
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/boot/grub2/custom.cfg</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:532
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you create <filename>/boot/grub2/custom.cfg</filename> and fill it with content, it is automatically included into <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> right after <filename>40_custom</filename> at boot time."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:542
#, no-c-format
msgid "Mapping between BIOS drives and Linux devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:543
#, no-c-format
msgid "In GRUB Legacy, the <filename>device.map</filename> configuration file was used to derive Linux device names from BIOS drive numbers. The mapping between BIOS drives and Linux devices cannot always be guessed correctly. For example, GRUB Legacy would get a wrong order if the boot sequence of IDE and SCSI drives is exchanged in the BIOS configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:550
#, no-c-format
msgid "&grub; avoids this problem by using device ID strings (UUIDs) or file system labels when generating <filename>grub.cfg</filename> . &grub; utilities create a temporary device map on the fly, which is normally sufficient, particularly for single-disk systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:556
#, no-c-format
msgid "However, if you need to override the &grub;'s automatic device mapping mechanism, create your custom mapping file <filename>/boot/grub2/device.map</filename> . The following example changes the mapping to make <literal>DISK 3</literal> the boot disk. &grub; partition numbers start with <literal>1</literal> and not with <literal>0</literal> as in &grub; Legacy."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: grub2.xml:564
#, no-c-format
msgid "(hd1)  /dev/disk-by-id/<replaceable>DISK3 ID</replaceable>\n"
      "(hd2)  /dev/disk-by-id/<replaceable>DISK1 ID</replaceable>\n"
      "(hd3)  /dev/disk-by-id/<replaceable>DISK2 ID</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:570
#, no-c-format
msgid "Editing menu entries during the boot procedure"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:571
#, no-c-format
msgid "Being able to directly edit menu entries is useful when the system does not boot anymore because of a faulty configuration. It can also be used to test new settings without altering the system configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:578
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the graphical boot menu, select the entry you want to edit with the arrow keys."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:584
#, no-c-format
msgid "Press <keycap>E</keycap> to open the text-based editor."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:589
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use the arrow keys to move to the line you want to edit."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:593
#, no-c-format
msgid "&grub; boot editor"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:603
#, no-c-format
msgid "Now you have two options:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:608
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add space-separated parameters to the end of the line starting with <literal>linux</literal> or <literal>linuxefi</literal> to edit the kernel parameters. A complete list of parameters is available at <link xlink:href=\"https://en.opensuse.org/Linuxrc\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:617
#, no-c-format
msgid "Or edit the general options to change, for example, the kernel version. The <keycap function=\"tab\"/> key suggests all possible completions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:626
#, no-c-format
msgid "Press <keycap>F10</keycap> to boot the system with the changes you made or press <keycap function=\"escape\"/> to discard your edits and return to the &grub; menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:633
#, no-c-format
msgid "Changes made this way only apply to the current boot process and are not saved permanently."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:638
#, no-c-format
msgid "Keyboard layout during the boot procedure"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:639
#, no-c-format
msgid "The US keyboard layout is the only one available when booting. See <xref linkend=\"fig-trouble-install-keyboard-us\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:645
#, no-c-format
msgid "Boot loader on the installation media"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:646
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Boot Loader of the installation media on systems with a traditional BIOS is still GRUB Legacy. To add boot parameters, select an entry and start typing. Additions you make to the installation boot entry are permanently saved in the installed system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:654
#, no-c-format
msgid "Editing &grub; menu entries on &zseries;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:655
#, no-c-format
msgid "Cursor movement and editing commands on &zseries; differ&mdash;see <xref linkend=\"sec-grub2-zseries\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:663
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting a boot password"
